contents.name: Figure Proj.09 - Project Triggers
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Common Domain::Project ABE::_ Project Addendum Figures::Figure Proj.09 - Project Triggers

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: Here we will define an Event as a “happening at a point in time”. We will define a Trigger as an event that requires a response, even if the response may end up being “no action required”. Since the definition of a trigger may be contextual (the same event may require responses from some groups only) then it may be best to model this as a role (Event plays role of Trigger)....

ownedComment.body: Here we will define an Event as a “happening at a point in time”. We will define a Trigger as an event that requires a response, even if the response may end up being “no action required”. Since the definition of a trigger may be contextual (the same event may require responses from some groups only) then it may be best to model this as a role (Event plays role of Trigger). A ProjectMilestone is modeled as an Activity rather than as an Event, so that it is a type of ProjectElement and can form part of a Project. There will be Triggers that may cause the generation of an Activity. For example, a network fault, Customer complaint or network infrastructure run-out. Also, completion of a ProjectMilestone may generate events e.g. payment to a Contractor. <Note>Note: This part of the model may change when the SID Event model is defined.</Note>

contents.name: Figure Proj.08 - Project Calendar
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Common Domain::Project ABE::_ Project Addendum Figures::Figure Proj.08 - Project Calendar

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: A Project has two different Calendar related requirements. ...

ownedComment.body: A Project has two different Calendar related requirements. The first is to have a Calendar that shows the working time periods, used to convert between working hours and elapsed days. For example, if we have a 10-hour Activity, that is due to start at noon on a Friday, and if working hours are 9:00am –12:00am and 1:00pm ‘till 5:00pm Monday to Friday, then the Activity will not be completed until 4:00pm on Monday. A Project also needs to keep track of working days and holidays. Each Project may wish to have its own working time Calendar (e.g. for projects in different countries with different hours of work), but it will be most effective for a Project to utilize or modify a standard calendar. The second requirement is to be able to show Activities on a Gantt chart. To do this, we can store the Activity start and end dates in a Calendar Entry For more details of the Calendar core model, refer to the SID Time Addendum. Following Figure shows Project linking to Calendar. A Project links to a single ProjectCalendar, which is a type of CompoundCalendar. The CompoundCalendar would normally be made up of a Standard Work Calendar storing all the public holidays for a Country or a State (refer SID Location model). In addition, changes to the standard calendar can be made in a ProjectSpecificWorkCalendar. The intention is to reduce work calendar maintenance by allowing for the sharing of standard work times. For Projects that span multiple Countries, then a Project may need to use more than one StandardWorkCalendar. In that case then the project will need to associate Activities with Countries and use the correct StandardWorkCalendar for scheduling.

contents.name: Figure Proj.07 - project roles
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Common Domain::Project ABE::_ Project Addendum Figures::Figure Proj.07 - project roles

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: Parties (Organizations and Individuals) can play various Roles in a Project. This could be at the Project, WBS or Activity level and so this has been abstracted to the ProjectElement level in this model....

ownedComment.body: Parties (Organizations and Individuals) can play various Roles in a Project. This could be at the Project, WBS or Activity level and so this has been abstracted to the ProjectElement level in this model. We will define an abstract role that all ProjectRoles will be derived from. A few concrete roles are shown as examples. Other roles may also be appropriate. Note that for implementation, PartyRole is most likely to be an Interface with ProjectPartyRole a root abstract class implementing the PartyRole interface. There will be other Role sets that may also be important for a Project. Only a few Project specific ones are shown here.

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: Following Figure also shows a new Entity, ProjectResource. For now, we will use a simple definition for ProjectResource, as being an input to an Activity that can be consumed, modified or utilized by the Activity....

ownedComment.body: Following Figure also shows a new Entity, ProjectResource. For now, we will use a simple definition for ProjectResource, as being an input to an Activity that can be consumed, modified or utilized by the Activity. e.g. If we have an Activity “Weld Chair” then we may have ProjectResources such as chair parts, welding rod, a welder tradesman, a welding machine and electricity. e.g. If we have an Activity “Upgrade Router” then we may have ProjectResources of firmware CD, technician, upgraded IO card, Laptop PC. <Note>Note that in reality, we don’t constrain ProjectResources only to Activity inputs but also allow other things that add to the ProjectCost to be included (maybe the cost of capital, if a Project involves borrowing money!).</Note>

contents.name: Figure Proj.02 - detailed structure
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Common Domain::Project ABE::_ Project Addendum Figures::Figure Proj.02 - detailed structure

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: Notice that the model the following figure shows the composite pattern and associations individually, rather than at the ProjectElement level. This has been done to help the understanding of the business rules. In the design model it may be worthwhile moving these associations to ProjectElement and implementing the business rules using a rules or policy engine....

ownedComment.body: Notice that the model the following figure shows the composite pattern and associations individually, rather than at the ProjectElement level. This has been done to help the understanding of the business rules. In the design model it may be worthwhile moving these associations to ProjectElement and implementing the business rules using a rules or policy engine. ProjectElements can be related to each other, for instance an Activity can have predecessor and successor Activities. This will be explored in more detail in the next section. ProjectElements of the same type can be arranged into trees. This is shown using the Composite pattern [GoF], with the restriction [DAG] denoting that the composite forms a directed acyclic graph (no loops allowed) or [Tree] denotes that it is a strict hierarchy (an element can have only one parent at a given point in time). Note that the WBS Element hierarchy is restricted to the same Project and the Activity hierarchy is restricted to the same Project/WBS Element.

contents.name: Figure Proj.01 - basic structure
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Common Domain::Project ABE::_ Project Addendum Figures::Figure Proj.01 - basic structure

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: Projects are made up of Sub-Projects, Work Breakdown Structure (WBS) Elements and Activities, as shown in figure 1. ...

ownedComment.body: Projects are made up of Sub-Projects, Work Breakdown Structure (WBS) Elements and Activities, as shown in figure 1. Projects can be established for many reasons in an Enterprise and Activities can cover any task in the Enterprise, from Strategic work, Product Development through to Repair and Maintenance. A Project can be thought of as a grouping of Activities to achieve one or more business goals. We will define an abstract entity “ProjectElement” that contains the common attributes and associations of Project, WBS Element and Activity. This will help in making the model simpler, more robust and more flexible. Note that in the model, many of the relationships have been generalized to link to ProjectElement. This allows the relationships to be defined at a high level (e.g. per Project) or at the lowest level (e.g. per Activity). To reduce data entry and data maintenance, the linkages should be made at the highest practical level. For example, if a Project is all at a certain Location then this linkage should be done at the Project level. If the Project is at 3 locations then link to the Locations at the highest level practical (e.g. a t the WBS or Activity level). Projects can be decomposed into smaller parts (sub-projects) forming a hierarchy. Similarly, WBS Elements are broken down using a strict hierarchy. Activities can also be formed into a hierarchy, allowing us to deal with them at both a summary and a detailed level. <Note>Note that Project, WBS Element & Activity are linked at the abstract level, allowing for greater flexibility.</Note>

contents.name: Figure Proj.00 - project vision
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Common Domain::Project ABE::_ Project Addendum Figures::Figure Proj.00 - project vision

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: Projects are executed to generate business value for the enterprise. This business value is specified by the Vision which addresses distinct BusinessObjectives of the enterprise. ...

ownedComment.body: Projects are executed to generate business value for the enterprise. This business value is specified by the Vision which addresses distinct BusinessObjectives of the enterprise. The Vision is the common understanding of all parties involved in a project (either directly or as a stakeholder) about the goals of a project, the key success criteria, timeline and impact of not doing the project.

contents.name: Figure Proj.14 - SCRUM blade
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Common Domain::Project ABE::_ Project Addendum Figures::Figure Proj.14 - SCRUM blade

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: Following Figure depicts the utilization of the generic project model presented in the special context of SCRUM by plugging in an extension blade. SCRUM is an iterative incremental process of delivery commonly used with agile software development. The SCRUM specific business entities were added specializing and concretizing business entities of the project ABE without changing or modifying the logical structure....

ownedComment.body: Following Figure depicts the utilization of the generic project model presented in the special context of SCRUM by plugging in an extension blade. SCRUM is an iterative incremental process of delivery commonly used with agile software development. The SCRUM specific business entities were added specializing and concretizing business entities of the project ABE without changing or modifying the logical structure. The SCUM blade specializes most of the generic project entities: In SCRUM ProjectElements are BacklogItems and Tasks (derived from acitivity); ProjectPartyRoles are the ProductOwner as the representative of the customer, ProjectContructor and the ScrumMaster. The deliverables of a SCRUM like project are WorkingIncrements; the project schedule consists of multiple Sprints. Specific to SCRUM is the Impediment that has no corresponding entity in the generic project model.

contents.name: Figure Proj.11 - Work Orders
contents.publish:qualifiedname: SID Models::Common Domain::Project ABE::_ Project Addendum Figures::Figure Proj.11 - Work Orders

publish:property.name: Description
publish:property.publish:value: To actually use resources, most organizations will require a formal signed document to authorize the usage. We will call this document a Work Order....

ownedComment.body: To actually use resources, most organizations will require a formal signed document to authorize the usage. We will call this document a Work Order. This model uses the Order Pattern by Riehle [Order Pattern]. Figure 3 shows that a WorkOrder may have many WorkOrderItems associated with it. These items would relate to lines on the order. Each WorkOrderItem may then have zero or more Fulfillments associated with it. Note that the WorkOrderItem may not equal the WorkOrderFulfillment as there may have been a substitution. e.g. 3 buckets of red sand on the Order, but 3 buckets of orange sand (an allowable alternative) actually sent
